NAT (Network Address Translation)
🎯 Objective

Learn what NAT is, why it is required, how it works, understand different types of NAT, and explore its practical applications in enterprise networks and AWS.

📖 What is NAT?

NAT (Network Address Translation) is a networking technique that translates private IP addresses into public IP addresses (and vice versa). It allows multiple devices on a private network to access the Internet using a single public IP address.

Without NAT, every device would require its own public IP address, which is impractical because IPv4 addresses are limited.

Why Do We Need NAT?

Imagine a company with 500 computers.

Without NAT:

Every computer would need a unique public IP address.
Public IPv4 addresses would be quickly exhausted.
Higher operational costs.

With NAT:

All devices use private IP addresses internally.
Only one or a few public IP addresses are needed to access the Internet.

How NAT Works
Private Network

Laptop A   → 192.168.1.10
Laptop B   → 192.168.1.20
Printer    → 192.168.1.30
       │
       ▼
+------------------+
| Router with NAT  |
| Public IP:       |
| 49.36.120.15     |
+------------------+
       │
       ▼
Internet

When Laptop A accesses a website:

The packet leaves with source IP 192.168.1.10.
The router replaces the source IP with its public IP (49.36.120.15).
The website responds to the router's public IP.
The router translates the response back to 192.168.1.10 and forwards it to Laptop A.
Types of NAT
1. Static NAT
One private IP maps to one public IP.
Commonly used for servers that must always be reachable from the Internet.

Example:

192.168.1.10  ↔  49.36.120.10
2. Dynamic NAT
Maps private IPs to a pool of available public IP addresses.
Public IP assignment changes based on availability.
3. PAT (Port Address Translation)

Also called NAT Overload.

Many private IP addresses share a single public IP.
Uses different port numbers to distinguish connections.

This is the most common type of NAT used in homes and small offices.

